Spring Framework 4.x + Jackson 2.12.6.1
Jackson was more forgiving and often fell back to java.util.Date parsing using the JDK’s default DateFormat — so MM/dd/yyyy worked out of the box.

Spring Boot 3.x + Jackson 2.18.2
Jackson dropped that fallback behavior.
Now it only accepts ISO-8601 (yyyy-MM-dd) by default unless you explicitly tell it otherwise.
That’s why your MM/dd/yyyy format, which used to “just work,” is now rejected with JsonParseError.



@Configuration
public class JacksonConfig {

    @Bean
    public Jackson2ObjectMapperBuilderCustomizer jsonCustomizer() {
        return builder -> {
            builder.simpleDateFormat("MM/dd/yyyy");
            builder.serializers(new LocalDateSerializer(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("MM/dd/yyyy")));
            builder.deserializers(new LocalDateDeserializer(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("MM/dd/yyyy")));
        };
    }
}


spring.jackson.date-format=MM/dd/yyyy
spring.jackson.serialization.write-dates-as-timestamps=false
